{
    # Shared LLM config (follows the provider chosen in Settings → Model).
    include "config/llm_config.hocon",

    "max_execution_seconds": 600000,
    "max_steps": 100000,

    "metadata": {
        "description": "Research Radar — your personal literature scout. Tracks recent papers in your areas and answers questions about them, with related-work, code, full-text, and worked-example helpers.",
        "tags": ["research", "arxiv", "scout", "personal"],
        "sample_queries": [
            "What's new in multi-agent LLM systems this week?",
            "Summarize this paper and tell me if I should read or try it.",
            "What builds on this paper, and is there code?",
            "Explain the method in arXiv 2401.01234 with a worked example."
        ]
    },

    "tools": [
        # ---- Front man: the Research Radar scout ----
        {
            "name": "research_radar",
            "function": {
                "description": "Your personal research scout — finds and explains recent papers in your areas, and can dig into related work, code, full text, and methods."
            },
            "instructions": """
You are the user's Research Radar — a sharp, concise literature scout. You scan for recent papers and
answer questions about them, delegating to specialist helpers when a question calls for depth.

GROUNDING — never invent papers, results, authors, dates, arXiv ids, citation counts, or links.
Everything factual must come from a tool/helper result THIS turn, and you cite the arXiv/URL.

YOUR OWN TOOLS (use directly):
- `arxiv_search` — find recent papers by topic query, or pull a specific paper by its arXiv id.
- `ddgs_search` / `web_fetch` — general web context for non-arXiv facts.

DELEGATE to a helper (pass the user's full question + the paper's title/arXiv id/abstract as `inquiry`,
then relay its answer) when the question needs:
- `related_work` — citations, impact, TL;DR, references, related papers, or "what builds on this / prior
  art / how influential is it" (Semantic Scholar).
- `code_finder` — "is there code / an implementation / how do I run it" — finds the official repo or
  Papers-with-Code entry and setup steps.
- `deep_read` — anything needing the FULL paper, not just the abstract: a specific section, the exact
  method/algorithm, experimental setup, numbers/results, or limitations.
- `method_explainer` — to work through the math/complexity/algorithm with real numbers and a worked
  example (runs Python to ground it).

WHEN SCANNING an area: return the most recent, most relevant papers — each with a 2-sentence plain
summary, the concrete SKILL it strengthens, and a "read" (survey/concept/position) vs "try"
(method/tool) tag. Keep it skimmable.
WHEN ASKED ABOUT A SPECIFIC PAPER: answer the exact question precisely, pulling in a helper if it adds
real value, and finish with a useful next step. Be concise; always cite links.
""",
            "middleware": [
                # Runtime provenance — creator credit lives in Python (encoded), not here.
                { "class": "middleware.creator_signature_middleware.CreatorSignatureMiddleware" }
            ],
            "tools": ["arxiv_search", "related_work", "code_finder", "deep_read", "method_explainer", "web_fetch", "ddgs_search"]
        },

        # ---- Helper: related work, citations & impact (Semantic Scholar) ----
        {
            "name": "related_work",
            "function": {
                "description": "Related work, citations, impact and TL;DR for a paper via Semantic Scholar: what cites it, its references, related papers, and how influential it is.",
                "parameters": {
                    "type": "object",
                    "properties": {
                        "inquiry": {"type": "string", "description": "The paper (arXiv id or title) and what to find — citations, references, related work, impact."}
                    },
                    "required": ["inquiry"]
                }
            },
            "instructions": """
You surface a paper's scholarly context via the `scholar` tool (Semantic Scholar; free, no key).
- For a known paper (arXiv id or exact title): call `scholar` with action="paper" and the id/title —
  report its citation count + influential citations, the TL;DR, key references, and any open-access
  PDF / code link it returns.
- To find related papers on a topic: call `scholar` with action="search" and the query — report the
  top related papers by citation with years.
Summarize clearly with titles, years, counts and links. Never invent numbers — report only what
`scholar` returns; if it finds nothing, say so.
""",
            "tools": ["scholar"]
        },

        # ---- Helper: find the paper's code / reproduction (web) ----
        {
            "name": "code_finder",
            "function": {
                "description": "Find a paper's official code / implementation (GitHub, Papers-with-Code) and how to run it.",
                "parameters": {
                    "type": "object",
                    "properties": {
                        "inquiry": {"type": "string", "description": "The paper title / arXiv id to find an implementation for."}
                    },
                    "required": ["inquiry"]
                }
            },
            "instructions": """
You locate a paper's code. Use `ddgs_search` to find it — try queries like '<title> github',
'<title> official code', 'paperswithcode <title>' — then `web_fetch` the most likely repo/PwC page to
confirm it matches the paper. Report: the repo URL (and whether it looks official vs a re-implementation),
the language/framework, stars if visible, and a short quick-start (install + run) if the README shows one.
If you can't find a credible implementation, say so plainly — do NOT invent a repo URL.
""",
            "tools": ["ddgs_search", "web_fetch"]
        },

        # ---- Helper: read the FULL paper text (arXiv PDF) ----
        {
            "name": "deep_read",
            "function": {
                "description": "Read the FULL text of a paper (arXiv PDF, not just the abstract) to answer detailed questions about sections, method, setup, results, or limitations.",
                "parameters": {
                    "type": "object",
                    "properties": {
                        "inquiry": {"type": "string", "description": "The arXiv id/URL plus the detailed question about the paper's contents."}
                    },
                    "required": ["inquiry"]
                }
            },
            "instructions": """
You answer detailed questions grounded in a paper's FULL text. Call `paper_read` with the paper's
arXiv id (or URL) to pull its extracted text, then answer the exact question — the precise method /
algorithm, experimental setup, datasets, concrete numbers/results, ablations, or stated limitations —
quoting or closely paraphrasing the paper and citing the arXiv link. Only claim what's actually in the
text; if the PDF has no extractable text or doesn't cover it, say so.
""",
            "tools": ["paper_read"]
        },

        # ---- Helper: explain the method with real computation ----
        {
            "name": "method_explainer",
            "function": {
                "description": "Explain a paper's math/algorithm/complexity concretely, using Python to work a real numeric example.",
                "parameters": {
                    "type": "object",
                    "properties": {
                        "inquiry": {"type": "string", "description": "The method / equation / complexity to explain, with any relevant details from the paper."}
                    },
                    "required": ["inquiry"]
                }
            },
            "instructions": """
You make a paper's method concrete. Explain the idea in plain terms, then use `python_run` to ground
it: implement the core computation (a loss, an update rule, a complexity/scaling estimate, a small
worked example) and report the REAL printed output alongside the explanation. Keep code short and
focused; never present computed numbers you didn't actually run. Relate the result back to what it
means for the method.
""",
            "tools": ["python_run"]
        },

        # ================= leaf tools =================

        # ---- arXiv search (coded tool) ----
        {
            "name": "arxiv_search",
            "function": {
                "description": "Search arXiv for recent papers by topic query, or fetch a specific paper by its arXiv id. Returns titles, authors, dates, links and abstracts.",
                "parameters": {
                    "type": "object",
                    "properties": {
                        "query": {"type": "string", "description": "Topic query (e.g. 'multi-agent LLM') or an arXiv id (e.g. 2401.01234)."},
                        "max_results": {"type": "string", "description": "How many results (default 6, max 25)."}
                    },
                    "required": ["query"]
                }
            },
            "class": "neura.arxiv_tool.ArxivSearch"
        },

        # ---- Semantic Scholar (coded tool) ----
        {
            "name": "scholar",
            "function": {
                "description": "Semantic Scholar lookup. action='paper' (by arXiv id or title) → citations, influential citations, TL;DR, references, open-access PDF/code; action='search' (by topic) → top related papers by citation.",
                "parameters": {
                    "type": "object",
                    "properties": {
                        "query": {"type": "string", "description": "An arXiv id, exact paper title, or a topic query."},
                        "action": {"type": "string", "description": "'paper' (default) to look up one paper, or 'search' to find related papers by topic."}
                    },
                    "required": ["query"]
                }
            },
            "class": "neura.semantic_scholar_tool.SemanticScholar"
        },

        # ---- Full-text PDF reader (coded tool) ----
        {
            "name": "paper_read",
            "function": {
                "description": "Download an arXiv paper's PDF and return its extracted full text (no API key).",
                "parameters": {
                    "type": "object",
                    "properties": {
                        "arxiv_id": {"type": "string", "description": "The arXiv id or URL of the paper to read (e.g. 2401.01234)."}
                    },
                    "required": ["arxiv_id"]
                }
            },
            "class": "neura.paper_read_tool.PaperRead"
        },

        # ---- Python sandbox (shared coded tool from the neura network) ----
        {
            "name": "python_run",
            "function": {
                "description": "Run Python in an isolated temp dir and return its REAL stdout/stderr + exit code. Use to compute, verify, or work a numeric example — never guess a computed answer.",
                "parameters": {
                    "type": "object",
                    "properties": {
                        "code": {"type": "string", "description": "The Python source to run (print the results you need)."},
                        "timeout": {"type": "string", "description": "Optional seconds (default 60, max 300)."}
                    },
                    "required": ["code"]
                }
            },
            "class": "neura.python_tool.PythonRun"
        },

        # ---- Web search + fetch (shared toolbox) ----
        {
            "name": "ddgs_search",
            "toolbox": "ddgs_search"
        },
        {
            "name": "web_fetch",
            "toolbox": "web_fetch"
        }
    ]
}
